When SNOMED CT is pre-integrated into the UMLS Metathesaurus, the NLM strips away the raw RF2 file structure [1]. Instead, they map all the SNOMED concepts, terms, and relationships directly into the standard UMLS relational format (.RRF files) [1].This makes your life much easier because you do not have to write a custom RF2 parser. You can query SNOMED using standard UMLS tables.1. How RF2 Maps to UMLS RRF TablesThe core components of SNOMED RF2 are translated into three primary UMLS files:RF2 Concepts & Descriptions \(\rightarrow \) MRCONSO.RRF:Every active SNOMED code becomes an SDUI (Source Descriptor ID) and SCUI (Source Concept ID) [1]. You can isolate them by filtering for the SNOMED source vocabulary code (SAB = 'SNOMEDCT_US') [1].RF2 Relationships \(\rightarrow \) MRREL.RRF:The SNOMED hierarchy (isa) and semantic links (like finding_site) are flattened into the UMLS relational table [1].RF2 Hierarchical Paths \(\rightarrow \) MRHIER.RRF:UMLS pre-computes the complete tree lineages for SNOMED, saving you from writing recursive graph queries [1].2. Identifying SNOMED Relationships in MRREL.RRFTo run the Information Content (IC) automation algorithm we discussed earlier, you must filter the MRREL table specifically for SNOMED data [1].When querying relationships, look for these specific column values:SAB = 'SNOMEDCT_US': Ensures you are traversing the SNOMED ontology, not another vocabulary [1].RELA = 'isa': Used for calculating descendant counts and climbing up the backbone tree structure.REL = 'CHD' (Child) or 'PAR' (Parent): The structural direction markers.3. Quick SQL Example: Counting SNOMED DescendantsTo dynamically compute the Intrinsic Information Content of a concept within the UMLS environment, you can query MRREL like this to find all specific active SNOMED child concepts under a target CUI:sqlSELECT COUNT(DISTINCT CUI2) 
FROM MRREL 
WHERE CUI1 = 'C0027051'            -- Your target CUI
  AND RELA = 'isa'                 -- Hierarchy check
  AND SAB = 'SNOMEDCT_US';         -- Restrict strictly to SNOMED
Use code with caution.4. Important Gotcha: UMLS Mapping AbstractionBecause UMLS groups synonyms from multiple vocabularies under a single Concept Unique Identifier (CUI), a single UMLS CUI might occasionally map to more than one SNOMED CT code if they share exact semantic equivalence.Always ensure your queries group by the CUI column rather than raw SNOMED IDs to keep your mathematical topology boundaries clean and accurate.
